1. d4 {The Queen's pawn opening which is one of the two most common opening moves in chess along with 1.e4}
1...d5 {Black replies in a symmetrical manner.1...Nf6 is also equally popular and leads to the Indian defence.}
2.c4 {The characteristic move of the Queen's Gambit. White intends to exchange the flank c-pawn for Black's central 
pawn on d5. If this is achieved then White will have two central pawns to Black's one which allows him to exert more 
control over the centre. This is one of the objectives of opening play.}
2...e6{Black declines the gambit pawn and this move characterizes the Queen's Gambit Declined or QGD as it is known.
Black playing 2...cxd4 is also  popular and is known as Queen's Gambit Accepted or QGA. If White were to capture the 
pawn by playing 3.cxd5 then Black can play 3...exd5 and replenish the centre with another pawn on d5. Also 2...c6 is played 
regularly leading to the Slav defence.}
3.Nf3 {A developing move that exerts control over the d4 and e5 squares.}
3...c6 {This pawn structure is found in the Semi-Slav defence.
This pawn structure is a mixture of the Queen's Gambit and the Slav.
Perhaps the name Semi-Slav is derived from this mixture. This is a solid system for Black because he has fortified the 
central d5 square with both the pawns on e6 and c6. He can develop his pieces by playing ...Nf6,...Nbd7,...Bd6,...O-O.
The only problematic piece is the light-squared bishop on c8 that can be developed by playing ...b6 later or even ...b5 after 
eventually capturing ...dxc4}
4.g3 {4.Nc3 leads to the main lines of the Semi-Slav. Here White is intending to develop the light-squared bishop on f1 to g2
and patrol the h1-a8 diagonal. In the Semi-Slav Black intends to play ...dxc4 in the near future and hence the Bishop 
on g2 will be in a position to exploit the weakening of the light squares.Since White is half-committed to play Bg2 soon, Black 
now has the opportunity to play 4...dxc4 5.Bg2 b5 and protect the extra pawn.}
4...Nf6{Black develops a piece instead.}
5.Bg2 {The c4 pawn could have been protected by 5.Nbd2 or 5.Qc2 but White is determined to gambit the pawn on c4}
5...dxc4{Black now takes up the sacrifice.}
6.O-O {White completes the development of his king-side as he now has to play actively to justify the loss of a pawn.}
6...b5 {Black had to play this immediately as 6...Nbd7 would be followed by 7.a4 where White will make it harder for 
Black to keep his extra pawn.If Black cannot keep the extra pawn then the opening moves ...c6 and ...e6 are not justified 
because the whole point of playing those moves was to strengthen the d5 square. Giving up the d5 square without the 
compensation of the extra pawn seems inconsistent and would allow White to take a firm grip on the centre.}
7.a4 {White attacks the pawn formation and threatens axb5 to weaken the h1-a8 diagonal.The bishop on g2 will be alive and kicking 
in that case.}
7...Bxb7 {Black develops the dormant Bishop and also counters the aforementioned threat by reinforcing the vigil on the 
h1-a8 diagonal. To reassess the position now, we can see that White has both the central pawns and also a lead in development.
Black has an extra pawn to hide his lag in development.The position is fairly equal and White needs to work harder to 
justify his choice of plan.Black's king-side is still under-developed and he needs two moves more to castle on the 
king-side and develop his pieces.Since the Black king is still stuck in the centre White needs to open up lines that will 
keep Black occupied and deny his King any semblance of safety on e8.}
8.Ne5{White takes the above ideas into consideration and decides to keep Black pre-occupied with other headaches.
This move attacks the weak pawn on c6 and White is threatening to play 9.axb5 to pile up pressure on the c6 pawn as the 
Bishop on g2 will be a force to reckon with.If Black plays 8...Nd5 to shield the c6 pawn then 9.e4! will kick the knight allowing 
White to have a firm grip on the centre.}
8...Qb6{Black defends the bishop on b7 as 9.axb5 cxb5 will deny White's bishop on g2 from having free lunch on b7.
Another possible move for Black would have been 8...a6 to add more support to the b5 pawn.Then 9.axb5 axb5 10.Rxa8 Bxa8 11.Nc3 
will allow White to attack the b5 pawn and not allow Black to develop his pieces easily on the king-side.}
9.b3!? {White attacks the pawn on c4 and threatens to win the extra pawn after 10.bxc4 bxc4 11.Nxc4. It is instructive to 
note that GM Khalifman is keeping Black occupied with threats and does not allow more important things like the development of the 
pieces.}
9...cxb3 {This is forced or else White regains the extra pawn with more activity.}
10.Qxb3 {White not only exchanges the pawn but also exerts more pressure on the b5 pawn.
Now 11.Na3 will allow White to attack the b5 pawn further.White is relentless in his execution.}
10...Nbd7? *{Black makes an error and is looking to swap the knight on e5. It would have been wiser to prepare for 
short castling by playing 10...Be7 11.Na3 O-O 12. Nac4 Qxd4 13.Bb2 with a great initiative for White.10...Qxd4 }

